{
  "answer": "**In \"The Seafarer\" (Chapter 5 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker describes how the cuckoo's mournful cry—alongside spring's blooming groves, fair boroughs, and bright meadows—urges the eager soul \"to set out on its journey,\" signaling the compulsion to depart on sea voyages despite the sorrow it sows.[^1]**\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 5 (*The Seafarer*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-f52e2e).\n\n> The groves bear their blossoms, the boroughs grow fair,  \n> the meadows are bright, the world rushes onward;  \n> and all this urges the eager of heart,  \n> the soul to set out on its journey, for one who so thinks  \n> to travel far on the flood-ways.  \n> The cuckoo calls too, with its mournful cry,  \n> summer's warden sings, sowing a sorrow  \n> bitter in the breast-hoard.[^1]\n\n(Note: A cuckoo's cry also signals departure in *Old English Elegies* Chapter 8—a rune-carved staff's message urging a woman to sail upon hearing it—but this is not \"The Seafarer.\"[^2]) \n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 8, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/08-nu-ic-onsundran-the-secgan-wille-treocyn-ic-tudre-/translation/#p-58bec2).",
